# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# CODEOWNERS — approver model template (StarLabs CI/CD)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# WHAT THIS FILE DOES
#   GitHub reads CODEOWNERS to decide who must approve a pull request. The owner
#   listed for a path is auto-requested as a reviewer, and — once branch
#   protection is on — their approval is REQUIRED to merge.
#
# THE APPROVER MODEL (read this before editing)
#   CODEOWNERS is read from the PR's *base branch*, not from main. That means
#   each app repo can carry a DIFFERENT CODEOWNERS on each protected branch:
#
#     • development branch's CODEOWNERS  → the development approver allowlist
#     • production  branch's CODEOWNERS  → the (usually stricter) prod allowlist
#
#   So a change merging into `development` is gated by development's owners, and a
#   change merging into `production` is gated by production's owners. Keep the two
#   branches' CODEOWNERS files intentionally distinct — that asymmetry IS the
#   feature (more eyes / fewer named people on prod).
#
# ENFORCEMENT — IMPORTANT, READ HONESTLY
#   This file ALONE enforces nothing. CODEOWNERS becomes a hard gate ONLY when
#   GitHub Team branch protection is enabled on the org, with:
#       • "Require a pull request before merging"
#       • "Require approvals" + "Require review from Code Owners"
#   Until Team + branch protection is turned on, this file is advisory: GitHub
#   will still auto-request these owners as reviewers, but it will NOT block a
#   merge that lacks their approval. See docs/GOAL.md §3 and docs/ARCHITECTURE.md §8.
#
# HOW TO SET REAL NAMES
#   1. Replace the placeholder @School-of-Excellence/maintainers below with real
#      GitHub usernames (e.g. @vignesh-027) or real teams (e.g.
#      @School-of-Excellence/prod-approvers). Teams must exist in the org and
#      have at least read access to the repo, or GitHub ignores the entry.
#   2. Copy this file onto each app repo's protected branches, then tune per
#      branch: a broader list on `development`, a tighter list on `production`.
#   3. Add more specific lines BELOW the default line to override ownership for
#      particular paths (last matching pattern wins).
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Default owner — every file, unless a more specific rule below overrides it.
# PLACEHOLDER: swap for real usernames/teams before relying on this as a gate.
*       @School-of-Excellence/maintainers

